metadata.name: Mineral Composition #7
metadata.description:
Since its conception, this project has been modified over the past seven months by adding new elements and techniques to improve its overall aesthetic and impact, as well as my own skills as a generative artist.
Mineral Composition is an artwork inspired by the natural beauty and complexity of minerals: crystalline and ordered arranges of ionic elements. As an admirer of nature, I have been particularly drawn to the way that just a simple atomic rearrangement in the presence of certain metals can result in a merge of vibrant colors, brightness, and contrast.
My deep appreciation for this subject grew even stronger during my master's degree in Materials Science, which led me to search for a way to incorporate this knowledge into generative art. The idea to use k-means clustering to play with mineral colors came to me during a casual chat with a very clever friend (Estienne). They suggested trying this machine learning algorithm, which involves grouping similar colors into clusters and selecting representative colors from each cluster.
I was immediately intrigued by the idea and decided to give it a try. I gathered a selection of 20 mineral images and used them as samples for the clustering system. The results were nothing short of stunning - the algorithm was able to identify and extract a wide range of colors from the minerals and would have been difficult to replicate using traditional methods.
I knew that this approach to color selection would be a game-changer for my artwork, and I was eager to put it into action. Using the colors extracted through k-means clustering, I was able to create a truly one-of-a-kind color palette for each minted generative token one that perfectly captured the essence of minerals in all their vibrant and varied hues. And the best thing is even with repeated picked minerals, the palette won't never be the same.
Additionally, the FF-based drawing can vary in three models and, when combined with various texture elements such as irregular grids, geometrical patterns, and stained canvases, provides the viewer with a pleasing experience by allowing them to examine every single detail across the entire canvas.
"The main intention was to create a piece that would have a fine art feel and be suitable for printing at high resolutions to be displayed as part of an environment's decoration. To achieve this, I took great care in crafting every detail of this work, ensuring that it could be reproduced and enjoyed in all its detail and intricacy by collectors.
Overall, Mineral Composition is an art piece that combines multiple basic and medium techniques of creative coding and machine learning. It is a project that captures the essence of minerals in a completely innovative way and will be a welcome addition to any art collection.

_______________________________
Variety of editions is guaranteed by several features:
* Backgrounds with paper colors or with a picked color from the mineral palette.
* 20 real minerals as color samples to create infinite palettes by k-means clustering.
* Controlled variety of scale;
* Controlled variety of particle number;
* Animation time;
* Symmetrical mode (mirror mode) possibility (15%);
* Three drawing models for FF filaments (opening and closing screws or spring screws.

_______________________________
Interactive instructions:
After finishing the animation, press:
* [L] to check your mineral and palette info;
* [K] to save your .png file in screen size (smaller);
* [n = 2 to 5] to save your .png file in A[n] ISO216 printable sizes;

Depending on the RAM and CPU usage, it takes from a few seconds to a minute to render the image.
Advice: the system needs enough free RAM for rendering A2 sized images. It was tested on Chrome, Brave, Firefox, Opera, Edge and Safari, but please make sure it works on your device before. 
_______________________________
Prints can be ordered. Shipping costs to discuss. DM me on twitter for more information!
_______________________________

metadata.name: INTERFERENCES #3
metadata.description:
INTERFERENCES is an abstract representation of the incredible collaboration between artists, collectors and developers on fxhash.

Each edition is composed of a multitude of lines representing each individual on the platform. The color of each line defines the role of each individual in this universe. Through their interactions, and the interferences they produce, each line participates in the creation of a common work.

Happy birthday fxhash! And congratulations to all those who work for its success.

Primary sales are donated to the Processing Foundation

[TOUCHSCREEN]
* Double Tap to save the current image

[KEYBOARD]
* Press [S] to save the current image
* Press [1] to save a 1500x2000 pixels PNG
* Press [2] to save a 3000x4000 pixels PNG
* Press [3] to save a 6000x8000 pixels PNG
* Press [0] to save 3 individual SVG for each color set of lines + the background image PNG
* Press [9] to save a grouped SVG of all the lines + the background image PNG

Artist: Estienne
Nov. 2022

metadata.name: Emotions #90
metadata.description:
1) INTRO (MUST READ)
"Emotions" is a unique Animated, watercolor or liquid painting-like abstract generative artwork which incorporates some "innovative" or unique techniques and approaches.

If find the above too selfish or wonder if its worth to buy this sh**t in a relative high price from an unknown "artist" please give some time to read the whole description. You will not regret!

I don't like to talk about myself or using marketing expressions, however sometimes have to, in order to clarify some points & spot some important features

All started as an exercise to shaders on Nov. 2022 and is the completion of this experimentation (rotating colors): twitter.com/Uniray_net/status/1587588272842280961 


2) SHORT BIO
I was always between graphics & programming. Was very good in both areas (as my teachers were saying) & remember me also drawing from childhood 
The first years i was focusing more in graphics (i was teaching graphics as well) and i was programming graphics for hobby

From 2005 & later i started a turn in my career & made programming my profession for the last 13-14 years (developer in some private companies)
In 2020 I started again a more serious involvement with graphics without knowing anything about NFTs or WEB3. And from 2021 i started getting more & more involved. Still so many to learn

I am new in gen art, started few months ago with plain javascript.
Started learning p5js in Aug. 2002 and shaders in Oct. 2022 & "Emotions" is my first "large" work. 
Already published some simpler & old works (eg. 3D) & things i developed as i was learning

3) FEATURES
I think i am presenting something relatively different with "Emotions" & always try to apply one of my favorite motto: "Lead, don't follow"

The general experience in programming & the fact that i had already programmed graphics in conjunction with my love for experimentation & searching behind the things, helped me to incorporate in "Emotions" some "innovative" i believe features & techniques (it sounds selfish but let me explain)

- First i am "proud" of the shader work. I developed completely custom "advanced" techniques that discovered after experimentation & some knowledge of course.

- "Emotions" includes 51 palettes (with several color each) that have been stored externally (in the application folder) as Adobe ".act" color table files so that avoiding hard coded (including all palettes in the code) consuming in this way resources eg. memory from user's system. I just load only the one palette i am going to use

- A fast svg Convolution kernel Matrix filter along with a displacement filter used for the texture

- Lastly & minor, you can switch Orientation (Portrait, Landscape, etc) & Resolution with the press of a key (no need to manually add params in the url)

From the above the most important part is the webGL shader.

4) CONCLUSION
"Emotions" is an animated watercolor painting-like (or liquid pigments material) abstract "live" work, that instead of staying static, starting with an initial state & slowly flowing, changing shapes & colors as sometimes happens with our emotions & feelings which may changed over time. 
Colors also represents emotions eg. red is for passion, green is the color of hope, etc 

Give some time to observe the progress and liquid feel and motion in shapes and colors.  Relax and look the flow and color diffusion - spread  & the whole "painting" to transformed slowly. 

KEYS:
- 1-4: Set resolution from 1x to 4x of the current dimension (slower performance in higher values)
- T: Texture on/off
- S: Save a png file with the current resolution

- P: Change orientation to Portrait (default). Aspect ratio 0.75
- L: Change orientation to Landscape with ratio 4/3
- O: Change orientation to Square (box)
  Due to some 1:1 ratio sensitive calculations, rendering output may differ between orientations

- Spacebar: animation on/off

MOUSE:
- Click: animation on/off
- Move: left - right on canvas (when in animation) to interact

----
Made with p5js & custom shaders. Pure code. No Images used

© Dec. 2022  @Uniray_net | uniray.net

Tilemoji #12
metadata.description:
This collection of low resolution generative art is presented using emojis rather than an image, so it can be copied like normal text. You are also welcome to take a screenshot for sharing or printing. Most results are designed to fit in a 280 character tweet, except for rare extra large variants. There are five different generative algorithms possible, each with their own set of parameters. Emojis are rendered using the Twemoji font and may look different in some environments.

Thank you for supporting my work during the first year of fxhash. For me it has been a life changing experience. I am forever grateful for all of the art and friendships we've created. Many of us have met on social media, so I developed this special project with a fun way to display and share. Congrats to artists, collectors, and developers for an amazing year!

This work is part of the fxhash anniversary event (#fxhashturnsone)

metadata.name: Memory #215
metadata.description:
"Memory" is an experiment in the dynamic interplay of soulful colors and forms. 
It is an exploration of smooth animation blending interesting fluid shapes. 
The piece is a continuous flow of forms and hues that seamlessly transition. 
The viewer can interactively zoom in and out and navigate to explore the full space of the artwork.
Furthermore the aspect ratio can be change to vary the framing of the piece, generating new impressions.
This invites the viewer to fully immerse themselves in the piece and experience it from different perspectives.
The name "Memory" reflects the intention to display an abstract representation of memories of a machine.
The colors aim to evoke a sense of emotion and depth. 

I created this work using twgl.js on a single fragment shader, my recent technique of choice. 

I hope you enjoy interacting with "Memory" and exploring the different aspects of the piece.

This piece uses webgl, it can thus only be viewed on browsers implementing webgl.

License: CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0
Dependencies: 
- twgljs - A Tiny WebGL helper Library (MIT license)
- psrdnoise.glsl (MIT license)
- isMobile (Unlicense)
For more information, view the license file

Interactions
'-' to zoom in. 
'+' to zoom out.
'f' to change the aspect ratio to fullscreen.
'1' to change the aspect ratio to square.
'a' to change the aspect ratio to portrait format.
'w' to change the aspect ratio to 16:9.
's' to save an image of the canvas.
't' to toggle the time (day/night) in the image.
'b' to toggle the frame.
'h' to increase the quality modifier (maximum is 3).
'l' to decrease the quality modifier (minimum is 1).
The quality modifier is a modifier on the width and height of the canvas.
Changing the modifier can affect the look of the image due to subpixel artifacts.
The modifier can be used to save higher resolution images.
Higher values of the modifier increase memory usage and can cause a browser or webgl instance to crash.
'arrow_up' to move up in the image.
'arrow_down' to move down in the image.
'arrow_right' to move right in the image.
'arrow_left' to move left in the image.
